intro:
The `+=` operator concatenates onto an existing array instead of overwriting it. Useful when an included file (or a base block) defines some items and you want to add more without losing the originals.

```
items = [
  {
    slot = 0
    material = STONE
  }
]

items += [
  {
    slot = 8
    material = DIAMOND
  }
]

# resolves to a 2-element items array
```

Without `+=`, the second `items =` would replace the first - last-wins for scalars, and the array is treated as a scalar value (not an object). With `+=`, the new items are appended in declaration order.

Real-world pattern: include a base file with default items, then `+=` to add menu-specific extras.

**Goal:** the starter has one item at slot 0. **Append** a second item at slot 8 (`material = EMERALD`) using `+=`, **without** removing the first.

